  "prompt": "What is a pulmonary embolism?",
  "response": "A pulmonary embolism (PE) is a blockage in one of the pulmonary arteries in the lungs, typically caused by a blood clot that has traveled from another part of the body, most commonly from the deep veins in the legs (deep vein thrombosis). When this clot breaks loose and travels to the lungs, it can:\n\n1. Block blood flow to lung tissue\n2. Reduce oxygen levels in the blood\n3. Damage lung tissue\n4. Potentially strain the heart\n\nSymptoms can include:\n- Sudden shortness of breath\n- Chest pain\n- Rapid heart rate\n- Coughing (sometimes with blood)\n- Leg swelling or pain\n- Fever\n- Excessive sweating\n\nRisk factors include:\n- Prolonged immobility\n- Recent surgery\n- Cancer\n- Obesity\n- Smoking\n- Certain medications\n- Genetic blood clotting disorders\n\nPulmonary embolism can be life-threatening and requires immediate medical attention. Treatment typically involves blood thinners, clot-dissolving medications, or in severe cases, surgical intervention.",
